thical\nFramework\nSkill\nProficiency\nIndustry\nspecific\nreadiness\nData\nQuality\nmeets \nthreshold?\nData Quality \nImprovement\nAdequateInadequate Yes\nTeam formation\nUnestablished\nEstablished\nTalent \nacquisition\nstrategy\nImplement Cont monitoring\nM H F R C\nInsuffient\nSkill Gap Suffiecient \nTalent\nNo\nTraining\nUpskilling\nIntra Upgrade\nCloud Setup\nTalent\nAssessment\nCompliance Gov\nFramework\nDevelop AI Ethics\nData Standardization\nM - Manufacturing  H - Healthcare  F - Financial Services  R - Retail  C - Construction\nAdequate\nResource\nAugmentation\nPlan\nInadequate\n43\nAGENTIC AI FOR EXECUTIVES\nB. Industry-Wise Readiness  \nBefore an organization moves forward with implementing Agentic AI, it is crucial to \nassess its readiness across several key areas. These evaluation parameters serve as \na checklist, helping organizations ensure they have the right foundational elements in \nplace before proceeding with agentic AI adoption. By evaluating each of these\n\ndata\nData \ncollection \nsystems are \noperational \n24/7 \nAt least 12 \nmonths of \nhistorical \ndata is \navailable \nInitial: Basic infrastructure, limited expertise, and early framework development. \nEmerging: Building core capabilities and developing talent, with early AI \nprojects in progress. \nDeveloping: Systematic integration of AI, skilled talent pool, and centralized \nAI governance. \nAdvanced: Full integration, mature AI capabilities, strong governance \nframeworks, and industry-leading innovation potential. \nAGENTIC AI FOR EXECUTIVES\n46\n \n \nD. Recommended Strategies \nVery High           High          Moderate           Initial \nReadiness \nLevel \nLevel 1: \nInitial \nLevel 2: \nEmerging \nLevel 3: \nDeveloping \nLevel 4: \nAdvanced \nCharacteristics\nMinimal \nunderstanding \nof AI \nExperimental AI \ninitiatives \nSystematic AI \nintegration \nTransformative \nAI capabilities \nKey \nIndicators \nLimited data \ninfrastructure \nBasic data \nintegration, \ni